<span id="freeTextContainer12999411645935730441">Great summary of the history of South Africa. It&apos;s a learning experience and wish I had read James A. Michener&apos;s books in high school history class. One thing that particularly stood out for me was that the truly violent and horrific events in the book weren&apos;t from the people I thought they were gonna be from. WE forget some parts of history sometimes. Having said all that though, I did not like that you could not connect with ANY characters in the book. By the end of the chapter, the character </span>
  <span id="freeText12999411645935730441" style="display:none">Great summary of the history of South Africa. It's a learning experience and wish I had read James A. Michener's books in high school history class. One thing that particularly stood out for me was that the truly violent and horrific events in the book weren't from the people I thought they were gonna be from. WE forget some parts of history sometimes. Having said all that though, I did not like that you could not connect with ANY characters in the book. By the end of the chapter, the character that you were reading about is dead. Not by anything related to the plot but just of natural causes. The time span in this book is over 500 years so it was more of a lecture and less of a story. There were MANY little great mini stories and some characters I would have liked to read an entire story about, but that wasn't the case. This distances you from the characters and makes the story sort of dull.</span>
